{"nodes":[{"pos":[12,67],"content":"Overview of Windows Programming in C++ | Microsoft Docs","needQuote":false,"needEscape":true,"nodes":[{"content":"Overview of Windows Programming in C++ | Microsoft Docs","pos":[0,55]}]},{"content":"Overview of Windows Programming in C++","pos":[574,612]},{"content":"You can use Visual C++ to write a wide variety of programs that run on a Windows PC (x86, x64 or ARM), on a Windows server, in the cloud, or on Xbox.","pos":[613,762]},{"content":"Well-written C++ programs are fast, efficient, economical in power consumption, and able to take full advantage of multicore and many-core devices, general computing on the graphics processing unit (GPGPU), and other recent advances in hardware.","pos":[763,1008]},{"content":"There are several broad categories of Windows apps that you can develop with Visual C++.","pos":[1015,1103]},{"content":"These categories have different programming models, or app models, which means that they use different libraries and APIs that provide access to the platform and provide user interface.","pos":[1104,1289]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows Universal apps<ept id=\"p1\">](#BK_WindowsUniversal)</ept>.","pos":[1299,1346],"source":"[Windows Universal apps](#BK_WindowsUniversal)."},{"content":"The third category of Windows apps was introduced with Windows 8, and support for this category of apps continues in Windows 10.","pos":[1347,1475]},{"content":"These apps are frequently referred to as just \"Windows apps\" and they include desktop and mobile apps that target a variety of devices.","pos":[1476,1611]},{"content":"You can write these apps in C++/CX, a dialect of C++ that includes support for Windows Runtime development, or in standard C++ with COM using the Windows Runtime Library (WRL).","pos":[1612,1788]},{"content":"These apps were originally designed to run full-screen, although in Windows 10 users have the option of running them in a desktop window.","pos":[1789,1926]},{"content":"These apps are touch-oriented, but it is easy to use the mouse to operate if users prefer or if a touch screen is not available.","pos":[1927,2055]},{"content":"These apps are distributed from the Windows Store, a fact which led to them being called \"Windows Store apps.\"","pos":[2056,2166]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Desktop, Server, and Cloud Applications and Games<ept id=\"p1\">](#BK_Native)</ept>.","pos":[2176,2240],"source":"[Desktop, Server, and Cloud Applications and Games](#BK_Native)."},{"content":"This category includes Windows Desktop applications, sometimes called Win32 applications since these applications were using the Win32 API on Prior to Windows 8, all Windows applications were in this category.","pos":[2241,2450]},{"content":"Applications in this category can use MFC for a user interface and ATL to interact with Windows components, which are typically COM objects.","pos":[2451,2591]},{"content":"Applications, components, or libraries written with standard C++ also fit into this category.","pos":[2602,2695]},{"content":"This category also includes using C++ for core components and computational code in the context of server and cloud programming.","pos":[2706,2834]},{"content":"Sometimes the performance-intensive code at the core of a server or cloud application is written in C++ to maximize performance.","pos":[2835,2963]},{"content":"You can compile such code into a DLL and use it from C# or Visual Basic.","pos":[2964,3036]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>.NET Framework applications<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[3046,3078],"source":"**.NET Framework applications**."},{"content":"Most .NET Framework applications are written in C# or Visual Basic, but you can also C++/CLI (the /clr compiler option in Visual C++).","pos":[3079,3213]},{"content":"We recommend using C++/CLI for a minimal interop layer in a larger application that includes managed and native code.","pos":[3214,3331]},{"pos":[3376,3398],"content":"Windows Universal Apps"},{"content":"With Windows 10, apps are able to run on all Windows 10 devices such as tablets and mobile phones, as well as on the desktop.","pos":[3402,3527]},{"content":"On the desktop, they are able to run as a desktop window, instead of always running full-screen.","pos":[3528,3624]},{"content":"These apps can also run on the Xbox, and on future devices.","pos":[3625,3684]},{"content":"The programming model for the two types of apps is different from Win32 desktop applications.","pos":[3686,3779]},{"content":"These Windows apps run on the Windows Runtime, which provides user interface elements, essential services for these apps and provides, and an interface to the diverse hardware devices that are supported.","pos":[3780,3983]},{"content":"These apps compile to native code and have a XAML user interface, or use DirectX.","pos":[3984,4065]},{"content":"You can also write <ph id=\"ph1\">[!INCLUDE[wrt](../atl/reference/includes/wrt_md.md)]</ph> components in native code that other Windows apps can consume—these include apps that are written in C#, Visual Basic, or JavaScript.","pos":[4066,4271],"source":" You can also write [!INCLUDE[wrt](../atl/reference/includes/wrt_md.md)] components in native code that other Windows apps can consume—these include apps that are written in C#, Visual Basic, or JavaScript."},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create your first Windows Store app using C++<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=534976)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Create your first Windows Store game using DirectX<ept id=\"p2\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=244656)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Creating Windows Runtime components in C++<ept id=\"p3\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=244658)</ept>.","pos":[4272,4595],"source":" For more information, see [Create your first Windows Store app using C++](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=534976), [Create your first Windows Store game using DirectX](http://go.m